  <sect2>
    <title>Installation</title>

    <para>
      Install the package by running the following commands:
    </para>

<screen><userinput>./configure --disable-nls \
            --disable-alsaconf \
            --disable-xmlto &amp;&amp;
make</userinput></screen>

    <para>
      Now, as the <systemitem class="username">root</systemitem> user:
    </para>

<screen role="root"><userinput>make install</userinput></screen>

    <sect3>
      <title>Command Explanations</title>

      <para>
        <parameter>--disable-alsaconf</parameter>: This switch disables building
        the <command>alsaconf</command> configuration tool which is deprecated.
      </para>

      <para>
        <parameter>--disable-xmlto</parameter>: This switch disables man page
        creation and ensures successful build without <command>xmlto</command>
        installed.
      </para>

    </sect3>

  </sect2>

  <sect2>
    <title>Configuration</title>

    <para>
      Note that all channels of your sound card are muted by default. You can
      use the <command>alsamixer</command> program to change this. Use
      <command>speaker-test</command> to check that your settings have been
      applied correctly. You should hear <quote>pink noise</quote> on your
      speakers.
    </para>

    <para>
      The first time <command>alsactl</command> program is run, it will complain
      that there is no state in <filename>/var/lib/alsa/asound.state</filename>.
      You can prevent this by running the following commands as the <systemitem
      class="username">root</systemitem> user:
    </para>

<screen role="root"><userinput>touch /var/lib/alsa/asound.state &amp;&amp;
alsactl store</userinput></screen>

    <para>
      The volume settings should be restored from the saved state during boot.
    </para>

    <para>
      All sound devices are not accessible for any user except <systemitem
      class="username">root</systemitem> and members of the <systemitem
      class="groupname">audio</systemitem> group. Add any users that might use
      the sound devices to that group:
    </para>

<screen role="root"><userinput>addgroup <replaceable>&lt;username&gt;</replaceable> audio</userinput></screen>

    <note>
      <para>
        You may need to log out and back in again to refresh your group
        memberships. '<command>su
        <replaceable>&lt;username&gt;</replaceable></command>' should work as
        well.
      </para>
    </note>

    <sect3 id="alsa-utils-init">
      <title>Boot Script</title>

      <para>
        To automatically store and restore volume settings when the system is
        rebooted, install the <filename>/etc/rc.d/init.d/alsa</filename> boot
        script from the <xref linkend="bootscripts"/> package.
      </para>

<screen role="root"><userinput>make install-alsa</userinput></screen>

    </sect3>

  </sect2>

